# Backend Rules (NestJS)

## Module Structure
Every domain module follows this pattern:
```
module-name/
  entities/         # TypeORM entities
  dto/              # Request/response DTOs with class-validator
  module-name.service.ts
  module-name.controller.ts
  module-name.module.ts
  module-name.spec.ts  # Unit tests
```

## Entities
- Use TypeORM decorators (@Entity, @Column, @PrimaryGeneratedColumn, etc.)
- Always include `createdAt` and `updatedAt` timestamp columns
- Use `uuid` for primary keys: `@PrimaryGeneratedColumn('uuid')`
- Define relations explicitly with `@ManyToOne`, `@OneToMany`, `@ManyToMany`
- JSON columns for flexible data: `@Column({ type: 'jsonb', default: {} })`

## DTOs
- Use `class-validator` for all input validation
- Create separate DTOs for Create, Update, and Response
- Use `class-transformer` `@Exclude()` to hide sensitive fields (passwords, tokens)

## Controllers
- Keep controllers thin -- delegate logic to services
- Use `@ApiTags()` and `@ApiOperation()` for Swagger docs
- Use `@UseGuards(JwtAuthGuard)` on all endpoints (or at controller level)
- Use `@CurrentUser()` decorator to access authenticated user
- Return proper HTTP status codes (201 for create, 204 for delete)

## Services
- All business logic lives in services
- Use constructor injection for dependencies
- Throw `HttpException` with appropriate status codes for errors
- Use transactions for multi-step operations

## Error Handling
- Use NestJS built-in exceptions: `NotFoundException`, `ForbiddenException`, `BadRequestException`, `ConflictException`
- Always provide meaningful error messages

## Environment
- All config via `@nestjs/config` from `.env` file
- Never hardcode secrets, URLs, or credentials
